# Svelte Components

This project uses **Svelte 5 runes mode** (enforced in vite.config.ts). Do not introduce Svelte 3/4 patterns in new or edited code.

## Props & state

- `$props()` with TypeScript types — `let { foo = "default" }: { foo?: string } = $props()`
- `$state()` for reactive local state
- `$derived()` / `$derived.by()` for computed values
- `$effect()` for side effects
- `$bindable()` for two-way bindable props
- `$inspect()` for reactive debugging (dev only)
- `<script lang="ts">` in components

## Events & bindings

- `onclick={handler}` event attributes (not `on:click`)
- Standard HTML attributes for events (`oninput`, `onsubmit`, etc.)

## Snippets

- `{#snippet name(params)}...{/snippet}` to define; `{@render name(args)}` to use
- `{@render children?.()}` for default content (not `<slot>`)
- Named snippets via `$props()` — not named slots

## SvelteKit

- Use `+page.server.ts` for sensitive data fetching and auth — never expose secrets in `+page.ts`
- Prefer form actions (`+page.server.ts` `actions`) for mutations; avoid client-only fetch for writes
- Use `+server.ts` for JSON API endpoints only
- The Svelte MCP (`list-sections` → `get-documentation`) provides current docs for `load`, routing, and forms

## Avoid (legacy Svelte 4)

- `export let` for props
- `$:` reactive statements (unless touching legacy code on purpose)
- `on:click`, `on:input`, etc.
- `createEventDispatcher`
- `<slot>` / `$$slots`
- `$$props` / `$$restProps`

## Before finishing

Use the Svelte MCP `svelte-autofixer` tool and fix all issues before delivering code.
